Time to go home!
After three-and-a-half months soaking up Florida’s sunshine and tropical warmth, I'm looking forward to getting home.

We’ll be just in time to watch spring arrive to color things up after a long, cold and very white winter in northern Michigan – or so I’m told. Home is where our family is and where we grow surrounded by love. I am looking forward to taking showers in my own bathroom, using a dishwasher, washing clothes in our laundry room, and most of all climbing into that roomy king-sized bed.

It happens every time we take off for parts unknown. We leave home to seek an adventure, get closer to nature and either reconnect with our friendly boating community, or to make new connections. Invigorated by setting out, towing our boat here or there, often-times with new navigation courses charted, we enjoy living mostly outside.

French toast com maple syrup 🍁
.
Receita super fácil e fica uma delicia para o café da manhã ou lanche da tarde.
.
6 fatias de Pão de forma
2 ovos
400 ml de Leite
Pitada de sal
1 c. Sobremesa de Açúcar mascavo (pode usar outra)
Canela em pó a gosto
.
Bata os ovos, acrescente os outros ingredientes e bate mais um pouco.
Numa frigideira coloque um pouco de manteiga e deixe esquentar. 
Passe a fatia do pão 🍞 nos ovos batidos uma a uma e coloca na frigideira. Deixa dourar bem e vira.

Prontinho! Só servir com maple syrup, manteiga ou alguma fruta da sua preferência.
Fica muito bom com bananas picadas.
Enjoy! ☺️"

Trader Joe’s had my back this week with super affordable salmon, so lunches this week have been a TREAT 😍 method below! 👇
.
.
I marinated 1 lb of salmon with a mixture of about 1 tbsp of honey, 2 tbsp soy sauce, and 1 tsp of sesame oil for about 30 minutes. Then, i preheated the oven to 400 F. While the oven was warming up, I heated a pan to medium high heat with a tbsp of oil. Once the pan was hot, I placed the fillets in skin side down for 1 minute. I turned down the heat to medium and cooked for another 2 minutes. After that, I flipped the fillets and baked them in the oven (I just threw the whole pan straight in!) for about 6 minutes (you might need to go longer if you have super thick fillets!) until the fish was nice and flaky. Served up here with curried freekeh, roasted broccolini and peppers! Bon appétit!"

The Upper Peninsula, also known as Upper Michigan, is the northern of the two major peninsulas that make up the U.S. state of Michigan. The peninsula is bounded on the north by Lake Superior, on the east by the St. Marys River, and on the southeast by Lake Michigan and Lake Huron. Geographically, the Upper Peninsula has a land boundary with Wisconsin, and over-water boundaries with Minnesota and Ontario (Canada). Upper Peninsula counties also include nearby islands such as Grand, Drummond, Mackinac, and Bois Blanc, and more distant Isle Royale. #rvlife #michigan #upperpeninsula"

This is the canal that we have here in Michigan: Sault St Marie, is the northeastern end of Michigan’s upper peninsula, separated from its twin city which is known as Sault St. Ontario. .
.
The nickname for it is called the Soo or the Soo Locks. .
.
It was founded in 1668. More than 12,000 years ago it was settled by the native Americans and was a long crossroad of fishing and trading for all the tribes along the Great Lakes. .
.
Sault Saint Marie in French means “the rapids of Saint Mary. .
.
My husband took me here on our honeymoon, learning and seeing this place was a sight to see. .
.
I love history and learning new things about my home state. .
.

While I greatly enjoyed our walk in the park today, it was bittersweet because we found signs posted that the fish in this section of the Huron River aren't safe to eat. This was one of the reasons we came back here. This park was our favorite spot to go trout fishing. Don't get me wrong, we like sport fishing as much as the next person, but we generally eat what we catch.. or at least we did. It hurts my heart. Our environment is shrinking, a part of our food source and livelihood is so close to being forever changed and soon there will be no going back. We (the collective \"we\") are running out of time to do anything about it. It boggles my mind that there are people who just don't give a shit about what they dump where or what the ramifications of that could be. \ud83d\ude14\n\n#pfas #poison #pollution #michiganwaters #donoteatthefish #bummer #whatthefuckarewedoing #disheartened #hur

I mentioned the Bruce had cool geology and I don\u2019t think anything can beat the flowerpots! These limestone sea stacks reside on the aptly named Flowerpot Island just off the coast. They were formed over the millennia by water, waves, ice and wind all hammering away at the cliffs along the island's shoreline. Softer rock layers slowly eroded and as the water levels waxed and waned post glaciation it finally left these two unique pillars that we see today. It's hard to believe that man had nothing to do with their formation and all it took was time and opportunity for nature and its power of erosion to do its thing. Two still exist today with a third having fallen back in the early 1900\u2019s. I\u2019m standing with the larger one in the second photo to give some scale. The appearance was canceled. Wilfred (1920 - 1998) had introduced Malcolm to the teachings of Elijah Muhammad. In 1952, Malcolm was paroled and went to Detroit to live with Wilfred. After Malcolm's assassination in 1965, he worked as a manager in public affairs until his retirement. Philbert (1923 - 1994) was a minister in Michigan and remained loyal to Eljah Muhammad when Malcolm left in March 1964. At the time he told the press that Malcolm \"may be a victim of great mental illness\" and called him \"a Brutus, a Benedict Anrold\" for leaving the movement. Two buildings - two campuses 
Picture 1: Michigan State University’s Linton Hall. Built in 1881, it is the oldest academic building on campus.

Picture 2: When Auburn University (as East Alabama Male College) opened in 1859, classes were held in a structure named "Old Main" on the current site of Samford Hall. On June 24, 1887, Old Main was destroyed by fire. The following year, Samford Hall was constructed, using, in part, bricks salvaged from the ruins of Old Main. The design of Samford Hall roughly mirrored that of Old Main, except that Samford Hall had two main entrances instead of Old Main's one."
